{"title_page": "The Level, Brighton", "text_new": "{{short description|Park in Brighton, UK}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = The Level\n| photo = File:The Level, Brighton (Northeastward View from opposite Oxford Street) (November 2015) (1).JPG\n| photo_width =\n| photo_caption = The northern half of the Level\n| map =\n| map_width =\n| type = Public Park\n| location = [[Brighton]], England\n| lat_d =\n| long_d =\n| source =\n| coords = {{Coord|50|49|50|N|00|08|00|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| area = 8 acres\n| created = 1822\n| awards           = [[Civic Trust Awards|Civic Trust Award]], [[Green Flag Award]], National Landscape award, [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]], Sussex Heritage Trust\n| parking          =\n| publictransit    =\n| transport        = [[National Cycle Route 20]], Buses: 21, 22, 24, 25, 26, 37, 37B, 38, 46, 48, 49, 50 and 81<ref name=\"BHCC\">{{cite web |title=The Level |url=https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/leisure-and-libraries/parks-and-green-spaces/level |website=Brighton & Hove City Council |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321222706/https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/leisure-and-libraries/parks-and-green-spaces/level |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n| operator = [[Brighton and Hove|Brighton & Hove City Council]]\n| status = Open year round\n| open = 24 hours\n}}\n'''The Level''' is an [[urban park]] in central [[Brighton]], on the south coast of the [[United Kingdom]]. The park is a triangle of {{convert|8|acre}} bounded by Union Street to the north, Richmond Terrace (A270) to the east, and Ditchling Road ([[A23 road|A23]]) to the west. In the past, the land has been used as a [[Ground (cricket)|cricket ground]] for the [[Prince of Wales]] and as a setting for huge dinner parties to commemorate events such as the defeat of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] and the coronation of [[Queen Victoria]].\n\nPresent day features of the Level include a grassed area with [[elm trees]] and outdoor seating, several caf\u00e9s, a [[skatepark]], a rose garden, a children's [[playground]] and a pond. The park was substantially redeveloped from 2009 onwards.\n\n== Overview == \nThe Level is in central Brighton, about {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of the seafront.<ref name=\"Fines45\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=45.}}</ref> It now covers {{convert|8.05|acre|ha}} but was originally much larger, encompassing the present-day Victoria Gardens and Valley Gardens to the south and the land now occupied by [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]] to the north.<ref name=\"NEB176\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=176.}}</ref> It forms a rough triangle enclosed by Union Street to the north, Richmond Terrace and Richmond Place (A270) to the east{{#tag:ref|Originally the southernmost part of Lewes Road.<ref name=\"Clunn152\"/>|group=note}} and Ditchling Road ([[A23 road|A23]]) to the west.<ref name=\"Clunn152\">{{Harvnb|Clunn|1953|p=152.}}</ref>\n\nThe park is surrounded by [[elm trees]] and is laid out in three sections. The northern part of the [[urban park]] is a grassed area. In the middle section is a [[skatepark]]. The southern part of the park is a children's [[playground]] and also includes two cafes, public lavatories, a pavilion which can be hired for community use, a pond with a fountain, a sensory garden and a zone for [[boccia]] and [[p\u00e9tanque]].<ref name=\"BHCC\" /><ref name=\"LUC\" />\n\n[[Brighton and Hove City Council]] added The Level to their Local List of Heritage Assets in 2015. The council's assessment described it as \"[a] well-designed municipal public playground, within an early public park ... [which] contributes greatly to the character of the area\".<ref name=\"LLHA-D\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/LLHA%20D.pdf|title=Local List of Heritage Assets: D|year=2014|publisher=[[Brighton and Hove City Council]]|format=PDF|accessdate=24 March 2020|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6gWQ8qmII?url=http://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/LLHA%20D.pdf|archivedate=4 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Formation and history ==\n[[File:The Level, a park in central Brighton, UK.png|thumb|right|250px|This map shows the bounds of the Level and nearby features]]\n[[File:The_Level,_west_side.jpg|thumb|right|250px|West side of the Level with elm trees, 2006]]\n<!-- The Level was mentioned in 1779 as grassland outside a farmhouse, which stood where the [[King and Queen, Brighton|King and Queen]] pub stands now across from Victoria Gardens. The area was much larger than the park today, extending from Victoria Gardens to the north, over the present site and into what is now [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]].<ref name=\"Bance\"/> -->\n\nLondon Road and Lewes Road, two major routes leading out of Brighton, were built along steep-sided valleys through which [[Winterbourne (stream)|winterbournes]] flowed intermittently. The valleys, and therefore the streams, met where The Level is now and flowed out to sea at [[Old Steine|the Steine]].<ref name=\"Antram4\">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=4.}}</ref> The land was always marshy and swampy and was never built upon.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> Instead, it became a popular place for public recreation and entertainment as Brighton grew into a fashionable resort town in the 18th century.<ref name=\"Fines25\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=25.}}</ref> After the town's authorities banned ball games and other traditional entertainments on [[Old Steine|the Steine]] in 1787, The Level became the focus for the early resort's sporting activities:<ref name=\"Seldon62\">{{Harvnb|Seldon|2002|p=62.}}</ref> four years later the Prince of Wales (later [[George IV of the United Kingdom]]) laid out a [[Ground (cricket)|cricket ground]] on the northern side. The [[Prince of Wales Ground]] hosted early [[First-class cricket|first-class]] matches and served as the home of [[Brighton Cricket Club]], one of the principal founders of [[Sussex County Cricket Club]] 50 years later. In 1822 the cricket ground moved to a nearby site called the Hanover Ground; after another move to the [[Royal Brunswick Ground]] on the [[Brunswick (Hove)|Brunswick estate]], it was established on its present site on Eaton Road in Hove in 1872.<ref name=\"Seldon62\"/> The Bat and Ball pub on Ditchling Road, facing the west side of The Level, commemorates the ground.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> Other popular events included the town's annual bonfire celebrations on [[Guy Fawkes Night]], regular circuses and fairs, and traditional activities such as [[bat and trap]]<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> and skipping. Writing in 1883, a contributor to the ''[[Sussex Archaeological Society|Sussex Archaeological Collections]]'' journal noted that the local [[Good Friday]] tradition of skipping was still maintained at The Level, where \"scores of skippers\" could be seen.<ref name=\"Underwood24\">{{Harvnb|Underwood|1978|p=24.}}</ref>\n\nAs well as these informal recreational events, The Level (especially the southern part, closest to the town centre) was used for formal, town-wide events and commemorations, such as the Prince's birthday celebrations.<ref name=\"Fines25\"/> The [[War of the Sixth Coalition|Allied Powers']] defeat of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] was celebrated in Brighton by the Great Peace Festival of August 1814. A mass dinner of roast beef and plum puddings was served at 75 double rows of tables for more than 7,000 people,<ref name=\"Fines26\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=26.}}</ref><ref name=\"Erredge299-300\">{{Harvnb|Erredge|1862|pp=299\u2013300.}}</ref> and the town's authorities organised activities such as running races, [[stoolball]], dancing and [[kiss-in-the-ring]].<ref name=\"Fines26\"/> The coronations of [[George IV of the United Kingdom|King George IV]] and [[Queen Victoria]] and the end of both the [[Napoleonic Wars]] and the [[Crimean War]] were celebrated with similar large-scale public feasts.<ref name=\"NEB177\"/>\n\nOn 22 April 1822, the 8 acres of land that nowadays form The Level was given in trust to Brighton by [[Thomas Read Kemp]] and other landowners.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/><ref name=\"Antram184\">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=184.}}</ref> Thereafter, apart from {{convert|105|acre|ha}} of [[downland]] near [[Brighton Racecourse]], far out of town on top of Race Hill, The Level was the only area of common land available to the town's residents.<ref name=\"OOB50\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=50.}}</ref> In the same year Union Road was built to connect the Ditchling and Lewes Roads, marking the northern edge of The Level, and the land to the north of it was sold. Local entrepreneur James Ireland established the Royal Gardens on this section, but the venture failed and the land was later sold again; [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]] was built on it from 1849.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/><ref name=\"Antram184\"/> Also in 1822 The Level itself was designed and laid out by architect [[Amon Henry Wilds]] and horticulturist [[Henry Phillips (horticulturist)|Henry Phillips]].<ref name=\"Antram184\"/> The elm trees, a gift to the town from the [[Henry Pelham, 3rd Earl of Chichester]], were planted in November 1844.<ref name=\"Dale217\">{{Harvnb|Dale|1976|p=217.}}</ref> Many were uprooted in the [[Great Storm of 1987]],<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> although at the time Brighton Borough Council was considering felling many of them because of an outbreak of [[Dutch elm disease]].<ref name=\"Trimingham43\">{{Harvnb|Trimingham|1999|p=43.}}</ref>\n\nBy the time [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]] became Queen in 1837, The Level was an important part of the growing resort of Brighton: the town extended for {{convert|1|mi|km}} northwards from the seafront, encompassing a \"splendid boulevard\" formed by the green spaces of [[Old Steine]], Valley Gardens (with [[St Peter's Church, Brighton|St Peter's Church]] as the centrepiece) and The Level itself.<ref name=\"Fines45\"/> Also at this time, when the success of [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway|Britain's first inter-city railway]] encouraged investment and speculation in the new form of transport, six routes were suggested for a railway line between London and Brighton. The shortest and most direct, covering {{convert|47.5|mi|km}} but requiring the most expensive construction work, would have terminated just north of The Level on the site of James Ireland's pleasure gardens.<ref name=\"OOB133\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=133.}}</ref> After [[Brighton main line|a line]] was built slightly further west in 1841, Brighton's population grew rapidly and its character changed.<ref name=\"NEB268\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=268.}}</ref> One feature of the mid- to late 19th century was a rapid growth in prostitution; it was common at The Level, when at night \"the scenes ... were said to beggar all description\".<ref name=\"OOB196\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=196.}}</ref> A police station was established in a small building at the southern end of the park in 1865. In 1919 it became the headquarters of the Brighton Parks and Gardens Department, and was later converted into a caf\u00e9.<ref name=\"NEB177\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=177.}}</ref>\n\nPolitical gatherings were also a feature of The Level. Among the regular events held there was the annual May Day rally and demonstration by the Brighton Trades Council, which was formed in 1890. These events \"became well known nationally\"; members included [[Margaret Bondfield]], who was employed as a draper's assistant in Brighton at the time and who later became the first female [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|cabinet minister in the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Fines78\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=78.}}</ref> Later, local resident [[Harry Cowley]] was an organiser of the barrow boys\u2014many of whom had been in the armed forces during World War I\u2014on nearby Oxford Street. In the early 1920s he negotiated permission for them to sell fruit and vegetables alongside the rose garden on The Level. This went on until the Open Market was built on the opposite side of Ditchling Road in 1926, when the boys moved there instead.<ref name=\"NEB194\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=194.}}</ref><ref name=\"OpenMarket\">{{cite web |title=The History of Brighton Open Market |url=http://www.brightonopenmarket.co.uk/history-of-brighton-open-market/ |website=Open Market |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322142700/http://www.brightonopenmarket.co.uk/history-of-brighton-open-market/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the 1930s, Cowley and his associates broke up a meeting of the Fascist League at The Level.<ref name=\"Cowley\">{{cite web |title=WW2 People's War - Harry Cowley |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/17/a4212217.shtml |website=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510054150/http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/17/a4212217.shtml |archive-date=10 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There was again a clash with fascists in June 1948, when members of the [[43 Group]] and Brighton locals prevented a meeting of [[Oswald Mosley]]'s [[British Union of Fascists]]. What became known as the Battle of the Level ensured no fascists returned to Brighton until the 1960s.<ref name=\"Bance\">{{cite news |last1=Bance |first1=M. |title=Brighton Level History |url=http://www.thepostmagazine.co.uk/brightonhistory/brighton-level |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Post Magazine |date=1 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321231149/http://www.thepostmagazine.co.uk/brightonhistory/brighton-level |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Greenstein\">{{cite book |last1=Greenstein |first1=Tony |title=Fighting Fascism in Brighton and the South Coast |date=2011 |publisher=Brighton History Workshop |location=Brighton}}</ref>\n\nThe children's [[playground]] was first constructed in 1927 by Bertie Hubbard MacLaren (Superintendent of Parks and Gardens).<ref name=\"Captain\">{{cite web |title=Captain Bertie Hubbard MacClaren |url=https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-8 |website=My Brighton and Hove |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321225924/https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-8 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He added a boating pond and a [[pergola]]. The pond has since been made smaller.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> During World War II, the [[Royal Engineers]] [[Eminent domain|requisitioned]] the [[Brighton Forum|Chichester Diocesan Training College for Schoolmistresses at Ditchling Road]];<ref name=\"NEB130\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=130.}}</ref> they put up several [[Nissen hut]]s on The Level to give them more space, and these temporary buildings stayed until well into the 1950s.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/>\n\n== Recent history ==\n\n===Peace camp===\nBrighton Women's Peace Camp was set up on the Level on 15 February 1983, in support of the [[Greenham Common Women's Peace Camp]]. At [[RAF Greenham Common]], women were protesting against [[cruise missile]]s from the USA being placed on British soil. The Brighton camp was one of many short-lived satellite camps that appeared around the United Kingdom in early 1983.<ref name=\"PC\">{{cite journal |last1=Carroll |first1=Sam |title=Brighton Womens Peace Camp, 1983: Second Wave Feminism and the Womens Peace Movement. |journal=University of Sussex Journal of Contemporary History |date=2005 |volume=8 |issue=Winter |url=http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/id/eprint/15795/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322134637/http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/id/eprint/15795/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast to the heavy-handed treatment of campers at Greenham by the authorities, Brighton participants said \"The Brighton Corporation have been very good. And the police have been very good.\"<ref name=\"Wimmin\">{{cite news |last1=Davie |first1=Michael |title=Who's afraid of wimmin? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/05/greenham3 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=5 September 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322134844/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/05/greenham3 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===BUFF===\nThe Brighton Urban Free Festival (BUFF) was held on the Level for the first time on September 1, 1984. It was a free music festival which aimed to promote local bands. It occurred again in 1985, then moved to [[Preston Park, Brighton|Preston Park]] in 1986, before returning to the Level in 1987, 1988, 1991 and 1992. Bands which played included [[Peter and the Test Tube Babies]], [[These Animal Men]] and [[Levellers (band)|The Levellers]].<ref name=\"BUFF\">{{cite web |title=Music and performance |url=https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-4 |website=My Brighton and Hove |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321225913/https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-4 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Skate park ==\n[[File:Brighton,_Skate_Park_(31840008245).jpg|thumb|right|250px|The redeveloped skate park]]\nThe first [[skatepark]] was designed by architects Murrin and Partners and built on the Level in 1978. There was a nearby skateshop called Pig City and in the 1990s there were regular skate competitions.<ref name=\"ArgusSkate\">{{cite news |last1=Team |first1=Timeout |title=LOCAL HISTORY: The Level Skatepark in the 1980s |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/16438921.local-history-the-level-skatepark-in-the-1980s/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Argus |date=16 August 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321224649/https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/16438921.local-history-the-level-skatepark-in-the-1980s/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the early 2000s, an [[elm tree]] next to the skate park became famous for having many shoes thrown into its branches. It then had to be felled in 2018 after catching [[Dutch elm disease]] from elms on the other side of the cycle path.<ref name=\"ShoeTree\">{{cite news |last1=Wadsworth |first1=Jo |title=Level skatepark\u2019s shoe tree to be felled after succumbing to elm disease |url=https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2018/07/05/level-skateparks-shoe-tree-to-be-felled-after-succumbing-to-elm-disease/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Brighton and Hove News |date=5 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322124923/https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2018/07/05/level-skateparks-shoe-tree-to-be-felled-after-succumbing-to-elm-disease/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe council received a lottery grant of \u00a32.2 million to build a new park, which was designed by Freestyle. The new park opened in June 2013.<ref name=\"ArgusSkate\" />\n\n== Redevelopment ==\nFollowing a successful [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]] grant request, the Level was substantially redeveloped from 2009 onwards, expanding MacLaren's original design: the skate park was moved and rebuilt, taking up what had previously been a grassed area; the pavilions were regenerated; the model boating pond was restored with a fountain; the playground was reconfigured; a sensory garden was added; a zone for [[boccia]] and [[p\u00e9tanque]] was provided.<ref name=\"LUC\">{{cite web |title=LUC picks up Sussex Heritage Trust award for The Level in Brighton |url=https://landuse.co.uk/news/luc-sussex-level-brighton/ |website=LUC - Environmental Planning, Design and Management |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=13 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321222655/https://landuse.co.uk/news/luc-sussex-level-brighton/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"LI\">{{cite web |title=Enhancing Brighton\u2019s Level |url=https://www.landscapeinstitute.org/news/enhancing-brightons-level/ |website=Landscape Institute |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161234/https://www.landscapeinstitute.org/news/enhancing-brightons-level/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe park won a Sussex Heritage Trust award in 2016 and is now [[Green Flag Award]] accreditated.<ref name=\"LUC\" /> It also won a [[Civic Trust Awards|Civic Trust Award]] and National Landscape award.<ref name=\"CTA\">{{cite web |title=The Level |url=https://www.civictrustawards.org.uk/winners/the-level1 |website=Civic Trust Awards |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161233/https://www.civictrustawards.org.uk/winners/the-level1 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NLA\">{{cite web |title=National accolade for The Level restoration |url=https://new.brighton-hove.gov.uk/news/2015/national-accolade-level-restoration |website=new.brighton-hove.gov.uk |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161508/https://new.brighton-hove.gov.uk/news/2015/national-accolade-level-restoration |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Antram|first=Nicholas|last2=Morrice|first2=Richard|title=Brighton and Hove|series=Pevsner Architectural Guides|publisher=Yale University Press|location=London|year=2008|isbn=978-0-300-12661-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clunn|first=Harold P.|authorlink=Harold Clunn|title=The Capital-by-the-Sea|year=1953|publisher=The Southern Publishing Co Ltd|location=Brighton|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Collis|first=Rose|others=(based on the original by Tim Carder)|title=The New Encyclopaedia of Brighton|edition=1st|year=2010|publisher=Brighton & Hove Libraries|location=Brighton|isbn=978-0-9564664-0-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Erredge|first=John Ackerson|title=History of Brighthelmston, or Brighton as I view it and others knew it|year=1862|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofbrighth00erre|accessdate=29 March 2020|language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Dale|first=Antony|title=Brighton Town and Brighton People|publisher=Phillimore & Co. Ltd|location=Chichester|year=1976|isbn=0-85033-219-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Fines|first=Ken|title=A History of Brighton & Hove|publisher=Phillimore & Co|location=Chichester|year=2002|isbn=1-86077-231-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gilbert|first=Edmund M.|title=Brighton: Old Ocean's Bauble|year=1975|origyear=1954|publisher=Flare Books|location=Hassocks|isbn=0-901759-39-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Seldon|first=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Seldon|title=Brave New City: Brighton & Hove Past, Present, Future|publisher=Pomegranate Press|location=Lewes|year=2002|isbn=0-9542587-1-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Trimingham|first=Adam|title=Trimingham's Brighton|publisher=Pomegranate Press|location=Westmeston|year=1999|isbn=0-9533493-2-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Underwood|first=Eric|title=Brighton|year=1978|publisher=B.T. Batsford Ltd|location=London|isbn=0-7134-0895-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Level, Brighton}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-25005565 BBC history of the Level in pictures]\n\n{{Brighton and Hove}}\n\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Brighton and Hove]]\n[[Category:1822 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Park in Brighton, UK}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = The Level\n| photo = File:The Level, Brighton (Northeastward View from opposite Oxford Street) (November 2015) (1).JPG\n| photo_width =\n| photo_caption = The northern half of the Level\n| map =\n| map_width =\n| type = Public Park\n| location = [[Brighton]], England\n| lat_d =\n| long_d =\n| source =\n| coords = {{Coord|50|49|50|N|00|08|00|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| area = 8 acres\n| created = 1822\n| awards           = [[Civic Trust Awards|Civic Trust Award]], [[Green Flag Award]], National Landscape award, [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]], Sussex Heritage Trust\n| parking          =\n| publictransit    =\n| transport        = [[National Cycle Route 20]], Buses: 21, 22, 24, 25, 26, 37, 37B, 38, 46, 48, 49, 50 and 81<ref name=\"BHCC\">{{cite web |title=The Level |url=https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/leisure-and-libraries/parks-and-green-spaces/level |website=Brighton & Hove City Council |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321222706/https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/leisure-and-libraries/parks-and-green-spaces/level |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n| operator = [[Brighton and Hove|Brighton & Hove City Council]]\n| status = Open year round\n| open = 24 hours\n}}\n'''The Level''' is an [[urban park]] in central [[Brighton]], on the south coast of the [[United Kingdom]]. The park is a triangle of {{convert|8|acre}} bounded by Union Street to the north, Richmond Terrace (A270) to the east, and Ditchling Road ([[A23 road|A23]]) to the west. In the past, the land has been used as a [[Ground (cricket)|cricket ground]] for the [[Prince of Wales]] and as a setting for huge dinner parties to commemorate events such as the defeat of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] and the coronation of [[Queen Victoria]].\n\nPresent day features of the Level include a grassed area with [[elm trees]] and outdoor seating, several caf\u00e9s, a [[skatepark]], a rose garden, a children's [[playground]] and a pond. The park was substantially redeveloped from 2009 onwards.\n\n== Overview == \nThe Level is in central Brighton, about {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of the seafront.<ref name=\"Fines45\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=45.}}</ref> It now covers {{convert|8.05|acre|ha}} but was originally much larger, encompassing the present-day Victoria Gardens and Valley Gardens to the south and the land now occupied by [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]] to the north.<ref name=\"NEB176\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=176.}}</ref> It forms a rough triangle enclosed by Union Street to the north, Richmond Terrace and Richmond Place (A270) to the east{{#tag:ref|Originally the southernmost part of Lewes Road.<ref name=\"Clunn152\"/>|group=note}} and Ditchling Road ([[A23 road|A23]]) to the west.<ref name=\"Clunn152\">{{Harvnb|Clunn|1953|p=152.}}</ref>\n\nThe park is surrounded by [[elm trees]] and is laid out in three sections. The northern part of the [[urban park]] is a grassed area. In the middle section is a [[skatepark]]. The southern part of the park is a children's [[playground]] and also includes two cafes, public lavatories, a pavilion which can be hired for community use, a pond with a fountain, a sensory garden and a zone for [[boccia]] and [[p\u00e9tanque]].<ref name=\"BHCC\" /><ref name=\"LUC\" />\n\n[[Brighton and Hove City Council]] added The Level to their Local List of Heritage Assets in 2015. The council's assessment described it as \"[a] well-designed municipal public playground, within an early public park ... [which] contributes greatly to the character of the area\".<ref name=\"LLHA-D\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/LLHA%20D.pdf|title=Local List of Heritage Assets: D|year=2014|publisher=[[Brighton and Hove City Council]]|format=PDF|accessdate=24 March 2020|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6gWQ8qmII?url=http://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/LLHA%20D.pdf|archivedate=4 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Formation and history ==\n[[File:The Level, a park in central Brighton, UK.png|thumb|right|250px|This map shows the bounds of the Level and nearby features]]\n[[File:The_Level,_west_side.jpg|thumb|right|250px|West side of the Level with elm trees, 2006]]\n<!-- The Level was mentioned in 1779 as grassland outside a farmhouse, which stood where the [[King and Queen, Brighton|King and Queen]] pub stands now across from Victoria Gardens. The area was much larger than the park today, extending from Victoria Gardens to the north, over the present site and into what is now [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]].<ref name=\"Bance\"/> -->\n\nLondon Road and Lewes Road, two major routes leading out of Brighton, were built along steep-sided valleys through which [[Winterbourne (stream)|winterbournes]] flowed intermittently. The valleys, and therefore the streams, met where The Level is now and flowed out to sea at [[Old Steine|the Steine]].<ref name=\"Antram4\">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=4.}}</ref> The land was always marshy and swampy and was never built upon.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> Instead, it became a popular place for public recreation and entertainment as Brighton grew into a fashionable resort town in the 18th century.<ref name=\"Fines25\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=25.}}</ref> After the town's authorities banned ball games and other traditional entertainments on [[Old Steine|the Steine]] in 1787, The Level became the focus for the early resort's sporting activities:<ref name=\"Seldon62\">{{Harvnb|Seldon|2002|p=62.}}</ref> four years later the Prince of Wales (later [[George IV of the United Kingdom]]) laid out a [[Ground (cricket)|cricket ground]] on the northern side. The [[Prince of Wales Ground]] hosted early [[First-class cricket|first-class]] matches and served as the home of [[Brighton Cricket Club]], one of the principal founders of [[Sussex County Cricket Club]] 50 years later. In 1822 the cricket ground moved to a nearby site called the Hanover Ground; after another move to the [[Royal Brunswick Ground]] on the [[Brunswick (Hove)|Brunswick estate]], it was established on its present site on Eaton Road in Hove in 1872.<ref name=\"Seldon62\"/> The Bat and Ball pub on Ditchling Road, facing the west side of The Level, commemorates the ground.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> Other popular events included the town's annual bonfire celebrations on [[Guy Fawkes Night]], regular circuses and fairs, and traditional activities such as [[bat and trap]]<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> and skipping. Writing in 1883, a contributor to the ''[[Sussex Archaeological Society|Sussex Archaeological Collections]]'' journal noted that the local [[Good Friday]] tradition of skipping was still maintained at The Level, where \"scores of skippers\" could be seen.<ref name=\"Underwood24\">{{Harvnb|Underwood|1978|p=24.}}</ref>\n\nAs well as these informal recreational events, The Level (especially the southern part, closest to the town centre) was used for formal, town-wide events and commemorations, such as the Prince's birthday celebrations.<ref name=\"Fines25\"/> The [[War of the Sixth Coalition|Allied Powers']] defeat of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] was celebrated in Brighton by the Great Peace Festival of August 1814. A mass dinner of roast beef and plum puddings was served at 75 double rows of tables for more than 7,000 people,<ref name=\"Fines26\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=26.}}</ref><ref name=\"Erredge299-300\">{{Harvnb|Erredge|1862|pp=299\u2013300.}}</ref> and the town's authorities organised activities such as running races, [[stoolball]], dancing and \"kiss-in-the-ring\".<ref name=\"Fines26\"/> The coronations of [[George IV of the United Kingdom|King George IV]] and [[Queen Victoria]] and the end of both the [[Napoleonic Wars]] and the [[Crimean War]] were celebrated with similar large-scale public feasts.<ref name=\"NEB177\"/>\n\nOn 22 April 1822, the 8 acres of land that nowadays form The Level was given in trust to Brighton by [[Thomas Read Kemp]] and other landowners.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/><ref name=\"Antram184\">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=184.}}</ref> Thereafter, apart from {{convert|105|acre|ha}} of [[downland]] near [[Brighton Racecourse]], far out of town on top of Race Hill, The Level was the only area of common land available to the town's residents.<ref name=\"OOB50\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=50.}}</ref> In the same year Union Road was built to connect the Ditchling and Lewes Roads, marking the northern edge of The Level, and the land to the north of it was sold. Local entrepreneur James Ireland established the Royal Gardens on this section, but the venture failed and the land was later sold again; [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]] was built on it from 1849.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/><ref name=\"Antram184\"/> Also in 1822 The Level itself was designed and laid out by architect [[Amon Henry Wilds]] and horticulturist [[Henry Phillips (horticulturist)|Henry Phillips]].<ref name=\"Antram184\"/> The elm trees, a gift to the town from the [[Henry Pelham, 3rd Earl of Chichester]], were planted in November 1844.<ref name=\"Dale217\">{{Harvnb|Dale|1976|p=217.}}</ref> Many were uprooted in the [[Great Storm of 1987]],<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> although at the time Brighton Borough Council was considering felling many of them because of an outbreak of [[Dutch elm disease]].<ref name=\"Trimingham43\">{{Harvnb|Trimingham|1999|p=43.}}</ref>\n\nBy the time [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]] became Queen in 1837, The Level was an important part of the growing resort of Brighton: the town extended for {{convert|1|mi|km}} northwards from the seafront, encompassing a \"splendid boulevard\" formed by the green spaces of [[Old Steine]], Valley Gardens (with [[St Peter's Church, Brighton|St Peter's Church]] as the centrepiece) and The Level itself.<ref name=\"Fines45\"/> Also at this time, when the success of [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway|Britain's first inter-city railway]] encouraged investment and speculation in the new form of transport, six routes were suggested for a railway line between London and Brighton. The shortest and most direct, covering {{convert|47.5|mi|km}} but requiring the most expensive construction work, would have terminated just north of The Level on the site of James Ireland's pleasure gardens.<ref name=\"OOB133\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=133.}}</ref> After [[Brighton main line|a line]] was built slightly further west in 1841, Brighton's population grew rapidly and its character changed.<ref name=\"NEB268\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=268.}}</ref> One feature of the mid- to late 19th century was a rapid growth in prostitution; it was common at The Level, when at night \"the scenes ... were said to beggar all description\".<ref name=\"OOB196\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=196.}}</ref> A police station was established in a small building at the southern end of the park in 1865. In 1919 it became the headquarters of the Brighton Parks and Gardens Department, and was later converted into a caf\u00e9.<ref name=\"NEB177\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=177.}}</ref>\n\nPolitical gatherings were also a feature of The Level. Among the regular events held there was the annual May Day rally and demonstration by the Brighton Trades Council, which was formed in 1890. These events \"became well known nationally\"; members included [[Margaret Bondfield]], who was employed as a draper's assistant in Brighton at the time and who later became the first female [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|cabinet minister in the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Fines78\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=78.}}</ref> Later, local resident [[Harry Cowley]] was an organiser of the barrow boys\u2014many of whom had been in the armed forces during World War I\u2014on nearby Oxford Street. In the early 1920s he negotiated permission for them to sell fruit and vegetables alongside the rose garden on The Level. This went on until the Open Market was built on the opposite side of Ditchling Road in 1926, when the boys moved there instead.<ref name=\"NEB194\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=194.}}</ref><ref name=\"OpenMarket\">{{cite web |title=The History of Brighton Open Market |url=http://www.brightonopenmarket.co.uk/history-of-brighton-open-market/ |website=Open Market |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322142700/http://www.brightonopenmarket.co.uk/history-of-brighton-open-market/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the 1930s, Cowley and his associates broke up a meeting of the Fascist League at The Level.<ref name=\"Cowley\">{{cite web |title=WW2 People's War - Harry Cowley |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/17/a4212217.shtml |website=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510054150/http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/17/a4212217.shtml |archive-date=10 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There was again a clash with fascists in June 1948, when members of the [[43 Group]] and Brighton locals prevented a meeting of [[Oswald Mosley]]'s [[British Union of Fascists]]. What became known as the Battle of the Level ensured no fascists returned to Brighton until the 1960s.<ref name=\"Bance\">{{cite news |last1=Bance |first1=M. |title=Brighton Level History |url=http://www.thepostmagazine.co.uk/brightonhistory/brighton-level |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Post Magazine |date=1 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321231149/http://www.thepostmagazine.co.uk/brightonhistory/brighton-level |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Greenstein\">{{cite book |last1=Greenstein |first1=Tony |title=Fighting Fascism in Brighton and the South Coast |date=2011 |publisher=Brighton History Workshop |location=Brighton}}</ref>\n\nThe children's [[playground]] was first constructed in 1927 by Bertie Hubbard MacLaren (Superintendent of Parks and Gardens).<ref name=\"Captain\">{{cite web |title=Captain Bertie Hubbard MacClaren |url=https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-8 |website=My Brighton and Hove |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321225924/https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-8 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He added a boating pond and a [[pergola]]. The pond has since been made smaller.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> During World War II, the [[Royal Engineers]] [[Eminent domain|requisitioned]] the [[Brighton Forum|Chichester Diocesan Training College for Schoolmistresses at Ditchling Road]];<ref name=\"NEB130\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=130.}}</ref> they put up several [[Nissen hut]]s on The Level to give them more space, and these temporary buildings stayed until well into the 1950s.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/>\n\n== Recent history ==\n\n===Peace camp===\nBrighton Women's Peace Camp was set up on the Level on 15 February 1983, in support of the [[Greenham Common Women's Peace Camp]]. At [[RAF Greenham Common]], women were protesting against [[cruise missile]]s from the USA being placed on British soil. The Brighton camp was one of many short-lived satellite camps that appeared around the United Kingdom in early 1983.<ref name=\"PC\">{{cite journal |last1=Carroll |first1=Sam |title=Brighton Womens Peace Camp, 1983: Second Wave Feminism and the Womens Peace Movement. |journal=University of Sussex Journal of Contemporary History |date=2005 |volume=8 |issue=Winter |url=http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/id/eprint/15795/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322134637/http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/id/eprint/15795/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast to the heavy-handed treatment of campers at Greenham by the authorities, Brighton participants said \"The Brighton Corporation have been very good. And the police have been very good.\"<ref name=\"Wimmin\">{{cite news |last1=Davie |first1=Michael |title=Who's afraid of wimmin? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/05/greenham3 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=5 September 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322134844/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/05/greenham3 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===BUFF===\nThe Brighton Urban Free Festival (BUFF) was held on the Level for the first time on September 1, 1984. It was a free music festival which aimed to promote local bands. It occurred again in 1985, then moved to [[Preston Park, Brighton|Preston Park]] in 1986, before returning to the Level in 1987, 1988, 1991 and 1992. Bands which played included [[Peter and the Test Tube Babies]], [[These Animal Men]] and [[Levellers (band)|The Levellers]].<ref name=\"BUFF\">{{cite web |title=Music and performance |url=https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-4 |website=My Brighton and Hove |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321225913/https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-4 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Skate park ==\n[[File:Brighton,_Skate_Park_(31840008245).jpg|thumb|right|250px|The redeveloped skate park]]\nThe first [[skatepark]] was designed by architects Murrin and Partners and built on the Level in 1978. There was a nearby skateshop called Pig City and in the 1990s there were regular skate competitions.<ref name=\"ArgusSkate\">{{cite news |last1=Team |first1=Timeout |title=LOCAL HISTORY: The Level Skatepark in the 1980s |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/16438921.local-history-the-level-skatepark-in-the-1980s/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Argus |date=16 August 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321224649/https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/16438921.local-history-the-level-skatepark-in-the-1980s/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the early 2000s, an [[elm tree]] next to the skate park became famous for having many shoes thrown into its branches. It then had to be felled in 2018 after catching [[Dutch elm disease]] from elms on the other side of the cycle path.<ref name=\"ShoeTree\">{{cite news |last1=Wadsworth |first1=Jo |title=Level skatepark\u2019s shoe tree to be felled after succumbing to elm disease |url=https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2018/07/05/level-skateparks-shoe-tree-to-be-felled-after-succumbing-to-elm-disease/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Brighton and Hove News |date=5 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322124923/https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2018/07/05/level-skateparks-shoe-tree-to-be-felled-after-succumbing-to-elm-disease/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe council received a lottery grant of \u00a32.2 million to build a new park, which was designed by Freestyle. The new park opened in June 2013.<ref name=\"ArgusSkate\" />\n\n== Redevelopment ==\nFollowing a successful [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]] grant request, the Level was substantially redeveloped from 2009 onwards, expanding MacLaren's original design: the skate park was moved and rebuilt, taking up what had previously been a grassed area; the pavilions were regenerated; the model boating pond was restored with a fountain; the playground was reconfigured; a sensory garden was added; a zone for [[boccia]] and [[p\u00e9tanque]] was provided.<ref name=\"LUC\">{{cite web |title=LUC picks up Sussex Heritage Trust award for The Level in Brighton |url=https://landuse.co.uk/news/luc-sussex-level-brighton/ |website=LUC - Environmental Planning, Design and Management |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=13 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321222655/https://landuse.co.uk/news/luc-sussex-level-brighton/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"LI\">{{cite web |title=Enhancing Brighton\u2019s Level |url=https://www.landscapeinstitute.org/news/enhancing-brightons-level/ |website=Landscape Institute |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161234/https://www.landscapeinstitute.org/news/enhancing-brightons-level/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe park won a Sussex Heritage Trust award in 2016 and is now [[Green Flag Award]] accreditated.<ref name=\"LUC\" /> It also won a [[Civic Trust Awards|Civic Trust Award]] and National Landscape award.<ref name=\"CTA\">{{cite web |title=The Level |url=https://www.civictrustawards.org.uk/winners/the-level1 |website=Civic Trust Awards |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161233/https://www.civictrustawards.org.uk/winners/the-level1 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NLA\">{{cite web |title=National accolade for The Level restoration |url=https://new.brighton-hove.gov.uk/news/2015/national-accolade-level-restoration |website=new.brighton-hove.gov.uk |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161508/https://new.brighton-hove.gov.uk/news/2015/national-accolade-level-restoration |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Antram|first=Nicholas|last2=Morrice|first2=Richard|title=Brighton and Hove|series=Pevsner Architectural Guides|publisher=Yale University Press|location=London|year=2008|isbn=978-0-300-12661-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clunn|first=Harold P.|authorlink=Harold Clunn|title=The Capital-by-the-Sea|year=1953|publisher=The Southern Publishing Co Ltd|location=Brighton|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Collis|first=Rose|others=(based on the original by Tim Carder)|title=The New Encyclopaedia of Brighton|edition=1st|year=2010|publisher=Brighton & Hove Libraries|location=Brighton|isbn=978-0-9564664-0-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Erredge|first=John Ackerson|title=History of Brighthelmston, or Brighton as I view it and others knew it|year=1862|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofbrighth00erre|accessdate=29 March 2020|language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Dale|first=Antony|title=Brighton Town and Brighton People|publisher=Phillimore & Co. Ltd|location=Chichester|year=1976|isbn=0-85033-219-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Fines|first=Ken|title=A History of Brighton & Hove|publisher=Phillimore & Co|location=Chichester|year=2002|isbn=1-86077-231-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gilbert|first=Edmund M.|title=Brighton: Old Ocean's Bauble|year=1975|origyear=1954|publisher=Flare Books|location=Hassocks|isbn=0-901759-39-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Seldon|first=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Seldon|title=Brave New City: Brighton & Hove Past, Present, Future|publisher=Pomegranate Press|location=Lewes|year=2002|isbn=0-9542587-1-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Trimingham|first=Adam|title=Trimingham's Brighton|publisher=Pomegranate Press|location=Westmeston|year=1999|isbn=0-9533493-2-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Underwood|first=Eric|title=Brighton|year=1978|publisher=B.T. Batsford Ltd|location=London|isbn=0-7134-0895-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Level, Brighton}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-25005565 BBC history of the Level in pictures]\n\n{{Brighton and Hove}}\n\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Brighton and Hove]]\n[[Category:1822 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Amakuru", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove quotes from kiss-in-the-ring, and redlink it", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Level,_Brighton"}
{"title_page": "Kristijan Golubovi\u0107", "text_new": "{{update|date=January 2016}}\n{{short description|Serbian public personality and MMA fighter}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Kristijan Golubovi\u0107\n| birthname = Aleksandar Golubovi\u0107\n| image = \n| imae_size =\n| caption =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1969|11|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Munich]], [[West Germany]]\n| conviction_status = Imprisoned (as of March 16, 2016)\n| charge = [[narcotics trade]] <br> illegal [[arms industry|arms]] possession <br> [[armed robbery]] <br> [[motor vehicle theft|car theft]] <br> [[extortion]]\n| conviction_penalty = 1993 <br> <br> 2003 - 2004 <br> 2005 - Jan 2009 <br> 2016 - 2020 (ongoing)\n}}\n\n'''Aleksandar ''Kristijan'' Golubovi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440 ''\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043d'' \u0413\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b}}); born 30 November 1969) is a Serbian public personality  and  [[Mixed martial arts|Mixed martial artist]].\n\nAfter spending four and a half years in prison for activities related to [[drugs]] in  [[Po\u017earevac]], he was released on January 9, 2009.\n{{As of| 2016}}, he is imprisoned again for the same level of crime, currently serving time for his penalty in Zabela Prison.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life, 1980s===\nBorn to Srboljub and Milanka Golubovi\u0107, Serb [[gastarbeiter|gastarbeiters]] living in Munich, Golubovi\u0107 did not meet his father until grade school since he was away serving a long-term prison sentence for taking part in a robbery with deadly outcome. His mother was a stewardess at [[Jat Airways|JAT]]. His father was imprisoned in [[Goli Otok prison]].<ref name=SPLIT/><ref name=JUTARNJI>{{cite web|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/novi-zivot-okorjelog-srpskog-mafijasa/363341/|title=Novi \u017eivot okorjelog srpskog mafija\u0161a|work=jutarnji.hr|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> Notable [[mafia boss]] [[Ljubomir Maga\u0161|''Ljuba Zemunac'']] was the godfather at Golubovi\u0107's [[baptism]].<ref name=\"JUTARNJI\"/>\n\nIn the mid-1980s Golubovi\u0107 befriended [[Joca Amsterdam]].<ref name=JUTARNJI/> In 1985 he befriended a Greek businessman whom he met through ''Zemunac'' in [[Frankfurt]].\n\nGolubovi\u0107 moved to Belgrade, [[Socialist Republic of Serbia|SR Serbia]] with his mother and sister in 1987; first settling in the [[Zvezdara]] neighbourhood and then moving to 50 Bra\u0107e Jerkovi\u0107 Street in [[Vo\u017edovac]]. Already no stranger to juvenile [[Juvenile delinquency|delinquent]] activity, the youngster continued along the same path with [[street fighting]], often involving [[knife|knives]] and [[gun|guns]]. He also started [[painting]], mostly while under arrest.\n\nIn December 1987, Golubovi\u0107 beat up a patron at a [[kafana]] in [[Bole\u010d]].<ref name=\"novosti.rs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.novosti.rs/code/navigate.php?Id=9&status=jedna&vest=52039&datum=2003-04-16|title=GAGI UHVA\u0106EN U BE\u010cU|work=novosti.rs|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1989, he instigated a fist fight versus Slavko ''Mija Pijuk'' Mijovi\u0107 (''Mija the Pickaxe'', the godfather of notorious gangster [[\u017deljko Ra\u017enatovi\u0107|''Arkan'']]) in front of ''Disco Luv'' in the Belgrade neighbourhood of Vo\u017edovac.<ref name=\"vreme-jun-2010\">{{cite web|first=Jovan|last=Milevi\u0107|url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=935224|title=Zatvorski sta\u017e Kristijana Golubovi\u0107a|publisher=[[Vreme]]|date=10 June 2010|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> Mija Pijuk's [[bodyguard]] Safet ''D\u017eimi'' Buljuku began firing shots at Golubovi\u0107, hitting him in the legs. In October 1989, Golubovi\u0107 initiated a brawl at the ''Branko Krsmanovi\u0107'' club, leading to several shots being fired as well.<ref name=YUR>{{cite web|url=http://www.yurope.com/zines/SAM/arhiva_4/0004.html|title=SAM arhiva broj 4 - : SAM 20/03/1996 - Intervju: Srbi iz podzemlja - Traze se zivi i vezani|work=yurope.com|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nIn the early morning hours of Sunday, February 25th 1990, Golubovi\u0107 was one of the perpetrators of an infamous act of violence in Belgrade's ''Hotel Ma\u017eestik.'' Along with his best friend at the time Dragan \"Gagi\" Nikoli\u0107, a heavily armed Golubovi\u0107 burst into the hotel's disco bar looking for a rival gangster. Since they didn't find him, 24-year-old Nikoli\u0107 and 20-year-old Golubovi\u0107 shot up and ransacked the place, destroying it in the process before fleeing the scene.<ref>[http://www.politika.rs/ilustro/2310/4.htm Gagijeva verzija, ''Ilustrovana politika'', April 26, 2003] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604170243/http://www.politika.rs/ilustro/2310/4.htm |date=June 4, 2009 }}</ref> Since the hotel's disco bar was a favorite [[mobster]] hangout, the incident gained them notoriety with the authorities   considering that many prominent and powerful mob figures were present to witness the shooting of bottles and shooting furniture he sure showed them just how destructive he can be.<ref name=BLIC>[http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Hronika/172615/Uhapsen-Kristijan-Golubovic-zbog-trgovine--drogom Uhap\u0161en Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 zbog trgovine drogom] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119194227/http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Hronika/172615/Uhapsen-Kristijan-Golubovic-zbog-trgovine--drogom |date=2010-01-19 }}; ''Blic'', January 16, 2010</ref><ref>[http://arhiva.kurir-info.rs/Arhiva/2004/decembar/18-19/H-02-18122004.shtml Jedva \u010dekam su\u0111enje, ''Kurir'', December 18-19, 2004]</ref>\n\nTo escape prosecution in Serbia, Golubovi\u0107 went back to Germany, but soon found himself serving a three-year sentence in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] on an armed robbery charge from a few years earlier. Due to being underage when the robbery was committed, he served the sentence in a juvenile prison. In 1993, German authorities extradited Golubovi\u0107 back to Serbia where he was wanted for a variety of criminal acts from the 1988\u20131990 period.<ref name=\"novosti.rs\"/>\n\nHe is well known for telling [[tall tale|tall tales]] about people no longer here to defend themselves. He is a long time friend of [[Milorad Ulemek]] and has maintained relations with ''Arkan'' through him. The story Golobovi\u0107 claims is true, that  Ulemek sent him to [[Erdut]] to the headquarters of the [[Serbian Volunteer Guard]] (''Arkanovi Tigrovi''), where he was asked to fight for them, but declined. Then he went as far as to say that Arkan asked Golubovi\u0107 to assassinate Serbian politician [[Vojislav \u0160e\u0161elj]], but he refused.<ref name=SPLIT>{{cite web|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/80192/Default.aspx|title=SPLITSKI GOST Kristijan Golubovi\u0107: Pucao sam u sto ljudi > Slobodna Dalmacija > Hrvatska|work=slobodnadalmacija.hr|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nGolubovi\u0107 married Danijela \u0110uki\u0107 and had a son Lazar with her while in Belgrade.\n\nOn 23 July 1994, Golubovi\u0107 had an altercation with Milorad Majki\u0107, owner of ''Casino Aleksandar'' at \u010cumi\u0107evo soka\u010de.<ref>{{cite web|first=M.|last=Derikonji\u0107|url=http://www.politika.rs/rubrike/Hronika/Kristijan-udara-levom-rukom.lt.html|title=Kristijan udara levom rukom|publisher=[[Politika]]|date=7 February 2008|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> Majki\u0107 claimed Golubovi\u0107 tried to extort DM 10,000 from him.\n\nGolubovi\u0107 left Serbia for [[Greece]] to avoid prison. There he became the worker of a former Yugoslav group that worked in [[Athens]]. \n<ref name=YUR/>\n\nGolubovi\u0107 was featured in a 1996 documentary about Serbia's underworld called ''[[Crime that Changed Serbia|Vidimo se u \u010ditulji]]'' that was filmed between 1994 and 1996. He is one of only a few individuals, out of dozens featured in the film, still alive today.\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2002 he escaped from [[Korydallos Prison]], where he was sentenced to 14 and a half years for stealing two [[BMW]] cars and an armed robbery.<ref name=BLIC/> During his time in prison, he maintained a relationship with [[Arkan]]'s daughter An\u0111ela Ra\u017enatovi\u0107; he said he wanted to marry her but the relation was short.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.revijad.co.me/index.php?nivo=3&rubrika=&datum=2009-01-14&brojms=342&clanak=756|title=Redirekcija|work=revijad.co.me|accessdate=8 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522012809/http://www.revijad.co.me/index.php?nivo=3&rubrika=&datum=2009-01-14&brojms=342&clanak=756|archivedate=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nGolubovi\u0107 got arrested in Greece on 25 December 2002 on a Serbian arrest warrant because of the criminal citation stemming from the July 1994 incident with Milorad Majki\u0107. The citation claimed Golubovic slapped Majkic while trying to extort DM 10,000 from him. Following three and a half month stay in [[detention (imprisonment)|detention]], he got [[extradition|extradited]] to Serbia on 16 April 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/info/vesti/index.php?yyyy=2003&mm=04&dd=16&nav_category=16&nav_id=106263|title=Izru\u010den Kristijan Golubovi\u0107|work=B92|date=16 April 2003|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> At the first court date in May 2003, Golubovic denied extorting Majic but admitted to slapping him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.blic.rs/stara_arhiva/hronika/43964/Samo-sam-ga-osamario|title=Samo sam ga o\u0161amario|newspaper=[[Blic]]|date=27 May 2003|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was arrested in [[Operation Sablja]], a crackdown on organized crime in Serbia following [[Prime Minister]] [[Zoran \u0110in\u0111i\u0107]]'s assassination, for being the leader of a criminal group that extorted \u20ac 15,000 from a businessman from [[Sremska Mitrovica]]; the sentence was initially 6 years, but the case ended with 1 and a half year.<ref name=BLIC/>\n\nOn the night of 17 March 2004, Golubovi\u0107 and famous Serbian [[turbo-folk]] singer [[Ceca Ra\u017enatovi\u0107]] (widow of the murdered ''Arkan'') gathered protesters in front of the government building in Belgrade to rally against the [[2004 unrest in Kosovo|situation in Kosovo]] where more than 36 [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Serbian Orthodox churches]] had been burned the same day in an outbreak of [[Albanians|Muslim Albanian]] violence against the [[Serbs|Serb]] natives of the province.\n\nOn 12 December 2005, Golubovi\u0107 got sentenced to six years of prison by the Special Court in Belgrade on illegal arms and [[racketeering]] charges of trying to extort \u20ac 15,000 from Petar \u017deravi\u0107, a former policeman from Sremska Mitrovica from April to June 2005 and the extortion of \u20ac 3,000 and [[gold jewelry]] theft from the Arsi\u0107's, a married couple from [[Aran\u0111elovac]]. The case was appealed ant the sentence got reduced to four and a half years, which he served at Zabela prison in [[Po\u017earevac]].<ref name=\"vreme-jun-2010\"/>\n\nOn 9 January 2009, he was released from the [[Po\u017earevac]] prison where he had spent four and a half years.<ref name=N247>{{cite web |url=http://www.novosti247.com/kristijan-golubovic-se-posvetio-duhovnom-zivotu-sada-radi-u-crkvi |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222031255/http://www.novosti247.com/kristijan-golubovic-se-posvetio-duhovnom-zivotu-sada-radi-u-crkvi |archivedate=2012-02-22 }}</ref>\nHe made a rap song together with [[Elitni odredi]] called ''Jack i Chivas'' (''[[Jack Daniel's|Jack Daniels]] and [[Chivas Regal]]''). He was denied entry to [[Croatia]] in 2009 when he was going to fight in the ''Millenium Fighting Challenge'' MMA event held in [[Split (city)|Split]], mayor [[\u017deljko Kerum]] denied his entrance and police were ready to stop Golubovi\u0107 if he would enter Croatia is all because he called the Croatian authorities To say that there was explosives on the bus that was entering Croatia a tactic Golobovic used previously, smiling as  he told reporters that he had a bad nightmare of losing badly to Kerum and that  no one scared his nerves  as much, they were out of control and I had to throw up, so he had to think of an ingenious plan, it's just like pulling the fire alarm in school when not ready for a big test, ha ha he laughed at this like it was a big joke,   Kerum said joke is on him, if he wants to live like a coward let him live it not me, he knows the deal with me in or out the ring, it's maybe his last fight when he was beat up and historical defeat he let down everything he stands for is giving him a nightmare the Albanian took his heart out ! So he can't  \"He has a history of crime and suspicious relations with the criminal world and is not welcomed to Split or Croatia, nor be a sport example\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/72161/kerum-kristijan-golubovic-ne-moze-biti-dobrodosao-u-split |title=Kerum: Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 ne mo\u017ee biti dobrodo\u0161ao u Split |magazine=[[Nacional (weekly)]] |trans-title=Kerum: Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 cannot be welcome in Split |language=Croatian |date=24 November 2009 |accessdate=24 July 2012 |archivedate=2012-07-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69OXdIpzK?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/72161/kerum-kristijan-golubovic-ne-moze-biti-dobrodosao-u-split }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bljesak.info/content/view/42404/159/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129025211/http://www.bljesak.info/content/view/42404/159/ |archivedate=2009-11-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 January 2010, Golubovi\u0107, his mother and five other members of his criminal group were arrested in Belgrade on charges of [[narcotics]] trade in [[Novi Pazar]] and Belgrade starting in August 2009. He and his two companions were intercepted at a drug exchange of 25&nbsp;grams of marijuana when they exited [[St. Mark's Church, Belgrade|Saint Mark's Church]].<ref name=N247/><ref name=BLICH>{{cite web|url=http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Hronika/172763/Kristijan-preuzeo-heroin-u-crkvi|title=Blic Online - Kristijan preuzeo heroin u crkvi|work=Blic Online|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> He had the previous week been stopped by police who found 10&nbsp;grams of marijuana in his [[Audi TT]]. His friend in the car claimed the marijuana was his and Golubovi\u0107 was held for 4 hours before being set free, his friend is awaiting trial. The police then searched his home in [[Vi\u0161njica, Serbia|Vi\u0161njica]] and found a gun and ammunition without a serial number, a Beretta was found in his mother's house.<ref name=N247/> He is to be sentenced for narcotics trade, illegal arms and explosives possession. They are all currently (April) in the central prison of Belgrade. He allegedly tried [[hanging|suicide by hanging]] in his cell the days following the arrest. The motive of the [[suicide attempt]] was that he felt devastated that he had caused the arrest of his mother who had nothing to do with this. She is quoted as having said, \"I should have aborted you\". He shares cells with \"Elez gang\", leader Darko Elez and [[Zemun clan]] hitman Nikola Baji\u0107. His wife was briefly held in March for the finding of a land mine in her car.<ref name=BLIC/><ref>http://www.glas-javnosti.rs/clanak/hronika/glas-javnosti-26-03-2010/kristijan-se-plasi-trovanja</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glassrpske.com/vijest/8/srbija/34581/lat/Kristijan-Golubovic-pokusao-samoubistvo.html|title=Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 poku\u0161ao samoubistvo|work=Glas Srpske|accessdate=8 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104224158/http://www.glassrpske.com/vijest/8/srbija/34581/lat/Kristijan-Golubovic-pokusao-samoubistvo.html|archive-date=4 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>http://www.glas-javnosti.rs/clanak/hronika/glas-javnosti-02-04-2010/kristijan-golubovic-optuzen-za-trgovinu-drogom</ref>\n\n===2010s===\nDuring the 2010s, Kristijan was constantly in and out of prison, awaiting trial. In early January 2016, Kristijan released a rap song with ''DeNiro'' called ''\u017divim kao \u0160ef''. Also, on May 9, he had his third mixed martial arts fight, returning to the sport 6 years after his previous fight, which he won by disqualification. It was held in [[Vienna]] against '''Agim Abdullahu'''. He lost the fight by [[Technical knockout|TKO]] in the first round. After the fight, Kristijan made statements  on social media that it was rigged and unfair, claiming it was the referee's fault.\nOn March 16, Golubovi\u0107 was sentenced to 4 years and 1 month in the Zabela prison. While in prison. On October 9, Golubovi\u0107 released another rap song called ''Moj Czas'' along with a fellow rapper from [[Poland]] called ''Brex''.\n\n==Popular culture==\nIn 1993 he appeared on the album ''[[Zbogom, Srbijo]]'' by [[Serbia]]n band [[Riblja \u010corba]], singing with band's [[Lead vocalist#Frontperson|frontman]] [[Bora \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107]] in the song ''Kamenko i Kremenko'' (Serbian names of ''Fred'' and ''Barney'' from ''[[The Flintstones]]'').\n\nHe was part of highly popular [[reality television|reality shows]], such as [[Farma (Serbian TV series)|''Farma'']] and ''[[Parovi]]''.\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws= \n| nc= \n| ko-wins= 1\n| ko-losses= \n| sub-wins= \n| sub-losses= 1\n| dec-wins= \n| dec-losses= \n| dq-wins= 1\n| dq-losses= \n| other-wins= \n| other-losses= \n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|align=center|2\u20131\n| Agim Abdullahu\n| Submission (guillotine choke)\n| Night of Gladiator\n| {{dts|2015|May|09}} \n|align=center| 1\n|align=center| N/A\n| [[Vienna]], Austria\n| \n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win \n|align=center|2\u20130\n|Stanislav Drakov \n| DQ (Drakov bit Golubovic's finger)\n| WKN Serbia - Kings of the Ring \n| {{dts|2009|December|13}} \n|align=center| 2 \n|align=center| N/A\n| [[Ni\u0161]], Serbia \n| \n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win \n|align=center|1\u20130\n|Marian Rusu \n| TKO (leg injury)\n| Ultra FC - Stop the Crime  \n| {{dts|2009|October|31}} \n|align=center| 1\n|align=center| 0:24\n| [[Subotica]], Serbia \n| \n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://kristijankikigolubovic.weebly.com/ Official website]\n*{{Sherdog}}\n* [http://blip.tv/play/hKYmgY%2BMYAI/ Documentary See You in the Obituary Full Movie]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-4824402008949268606 Interview with Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 on Palma television]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golubovic, Kristijan}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Escapees from Greek detention]]\n[[Category:Heavyweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mobsters from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Munich]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Serbian male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Serbian mobsters]]\n[[Category:Serbian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{update|date=January 2016}}\n{{short description|Serbian public personality and MMA fighter}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Kristijan Golubovi\u0107\n| birthname = Aleksandar Golubovi\u0107\n| image = \n| imae_size =\n| caption =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1969|11|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Munich]], [[West Germany]]\n| conviction_status = Imprisoned (as of March 16, 2016)\n| charge = [[narcotics trade]] <br> illegal [[arms industry|arms]] possession <br> [[armed robbery]] <br> [[motor vehicle theft|car theft]] <br> [[extortion]]\n| conviction_penalty = 1993 <br> <br> 2003 - 2004 <br> 2005 - Jan 2009 <br> 2016 - 2020 (ongoing)\n}}\n\n'''Aleksandar ''Kristijan'' Golubovi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440 ''\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043d'' \u0413\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b}}); born 30 November 1969) is a Serbian public personality  and  [[Mixed martial arts|Mixed martial artist]].\n\nAfter spending four and a half years in prison for activities related to [[drugs]] in  [[Po\u017earevac]], he was released on January 9, 2009.\n{{As of| 2016}}, he is imprisoned again for the same level of crime, currently serving time for his penalty in Zabela Prison.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life, 1980s===\nBorn to Srboljub and Milanka Golubovi\u0107, Serb [[gastarbeiter|gastarbeiters]] living in Munich, Golubovi\u0107 did not meet his father until grade school since he was away serving a long-term prison sentence for taking part in a robbery with deadly outcome. His mother was a stewardess at [[Jat Airways|JAT]]. His father was imprisoned in [[Goli Otok prison]].<ref name=SPLIT/><ref name=JUTARNJI>{{cite web|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/novi-zivot-okorjelog-srpskog-mafijasa/363341/|title=Novi \u017eivot okorjelog srpskog mafija\u0161a|work=jutarnji.hr|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> Notable [[mafia boss]] [[Ljubomir Maga\u0161|''Ljuba Zemunac'']] was the godfather at Golubovi\u0107's [[baptism]].<ref name=\"JUTARNJI\"/>\n\nIn the mid-1980s Golubovi\u0107 befriended [[Joca Amsterdam]].<ref name=JUTARNJI/> In 1985 he befriended a Greek businessman whom he met through ''Zemunac'' in [[Frankfurt]].\n\nGolubovi\u0107 moved to Belgrade, [[Socialist Republic of Serbia|SR Serbia]] with his mother and sister in 1987; first settling in the [[Zvezdara]] neighbourhood and then moving to 50 Bra\u0107e Jerkovi\u0107 Street in [[Vo\u017edovac]]. Already no stranger to juvenile [[delinquent]] activity, the youngster continued along the same path with [[street fighting]], often involving [[knife|knives]] and [[gun|guns]]. He also started [[painting]], mostly while under arrest.\n\nIn December 1987, Golubovi\u0107 beat up a patron at a [[kafana]] in [[Bole\u010d]].<ref name=\"novosti.rs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.novosti.rs/code/navigate.php?Id=9&status=jedna&vest=52039&datum=2003-04-16|title=GAGI UHVA\u0106EN U BE\u010cU|work=novosti.rs|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1989, he instigated a fist fight versus Slavko ''Mija Pijuk'' Mijovi\u0107 (''Mija the Pickaxe'', the godfather of notorious gangster [[\u017deljko Ra\u017enatovi\u0107|''Arkan'']]) in front of ''Disco Luv'' in the Belgrade neighbourhood of Vo\u017edovac.<ref name=\"vreme-jun-2010\">{{cite web|first=Jovan|last=Milevi\u0107|url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=935224|title=Zatvorski sta\u017e Kristijana Golubovi\u0107a|publisher=[[Vreme]]|date=10 June 2010|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> Mija Pijuk's [[bodyguard]] Safet ''D\u017eimi'' Buljuku began firing shots at Golubovi\u0107, hitting him in the legs. In October 1989, Golubovi\u0107 initiated a brawl at the ''Branko Krsmanovi\u0107'' club, leading to several shots being fired as well.<ref name=YUR>{{cite web|url=http://www.yurope.com/zines/SAM/arhiva_4/0004.html|title=SAM arhiva broj 4 - : SAM 20/03/1996 - Intervju: Srbi iz podzemlja - Traze se zivi i vezani|work=yurope.com|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nIn the early morning hours of Sunday, February 25th 1990, Golubovi\u0107 was one of the perpetrators of an infamous act of violence in Belgrade's ''Hotel Ma\u017eestik.'' Along with his best friend at the time Dragan \"Gagi\" Nikoli\u0107, a heavily armed Golubovi\u0107 burst into the hotel's disco bar looking for a rival gangster. Since they didn't find him, 24-year-old Nikoli\u0107 and 20-year-old Golubovi\u0107 shot up and ransacked the place, destroying it in the process before fleeing the scene.<ref>[http://www.politika.rs/ilustro/2310/4.htm Gagijeva verzija, ''Ilustrovana politika'', April 26, 2003] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604170243/http://www.politika.rs/ilustro/2310/4.htm |date=June 4, 2009 }}</ref> Since the hotel's disco bar was a favorite [[mobster]] hangout, the incident gained them notoriety with the authorities   considering that many prominent and powerful mob figures were present to witness the shooting of bottles and shooting furniture he sure showed them just how destructive he can be.<ref name=BLIC>[http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Hronika/172615/Uhapsen-Kristijan-Golubovic-zbog-trgovine--drogom Uhap\u0161en Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 zbog trgovine drogom] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119194227/http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Hronika/172615/Uhapsen-Kristijan-Golubovic-zbog-trgovine--drogom |date=2010-01-19 }}; ''Blic'', January 16, 2010</ref><ref>[http://arhiva.kurir-info.rs/Arhiva/2004/decembar/18-19/H-02-18122004.shtml Jedva \u010dekam su\u0111enje, ''Kurir'', December 18-19, 2004]</ref>\n\nTo escape prosecution in Serbia, Golubovi\u0107 went back to Germany, but soon found himself serving a three-year sentence in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] on an armed robbery charge from a few years earlier. Due to being underage when the robbery was committed, he served the sentence in a juvenile prison. In 1993, German authorities extradited Golubovi\u0107 back to Serbia where he was wanted for a variety of criminal acts from the 1988\u20131990 period.<ref name=\"novosti.rs\"/>\n\nHe is well known for telling [[tall tale|tall tales]] about people no longer here to defend themselves. He is a long time friend of [[Milorad Ulemek]] and has maintained relations with ''Arkan'' through him. The story Golobovi\u0107 claims is true, that  Ulemek sent him to [[Erdut]] to the headquarters of the [[Serbian Volunteer Guard]] (''Arkanovi Tigrovi''), where he was asked to fight for them, but declined. Then he went as far as to say that Arkan asked Golubovi\u0107 to assassinate Serbian politician [[Vojislav \u0160e\u0161elj]], but he refused.<ref name=SPLIT>{{cite web|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/80192/Default.aspx|title=SPLITSKI GOST Kristijan Golubovi\u0107: Pucao sam u sto ljudi > Slobodna Dalmacija > Hrvatska|work=slobodnadalmacija.hr|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nGolubovi\u0107 married Danijela \u0110uki\u0107 and had a son Lazar with her while in Belgrade.\n\nOn 23 July 1994, Golubovi\u0107 had an altercation with Milorad Majki\u0107, owner of ''Casino Aleksandar'' at \u010cumi\u0107evo soka\u010de.<ref>{{cite web|first=M.|last=Derikonji\u0107|url=http://www.politika.rs/rubrike/Hronika/Kristijan-udara-levom-rukom.lt.html|title=Kristijan udara levom rukom|publisher=[[Politika]]|date=7 February 2008|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> Majki\u0107 claimed Golubovi\u0107 tried to extort DM 10,000 from him.\n\nGolubovi\u0107 left Serbia for [[Greece]] to avoid prison. There he became the worker of a former Yugoslav group that worked in [[Athens]]. \n<ref name=YUR/>\n\nGolubovi\u0107 was featured in a 1996 documentary about Serbia's underworld called ''[[Crime that Changed Serbia|Vidimo se u \u010ditulji]]'' that was filmed between 1994 and 1996. He is one of only a few individuals, out of dozens featured in the film, still alive today.\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2002 he escaped from [[Korydallos Prison]], where he was sentenced to 14 and a half years for stealing two [[BMW]] cars and an armed robbery.<ref name=BLIC/> During his time in prison, he maintained a relationship with [[Arkan]]'s daughter An\u0111ela Ra\u017enatovi\u0107; he said he wanted to marry her but the relation was short.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.revijad.co.me/index.php?nivo=3&rubrika=&datum=2009-01-14&brojms=342&clanak=756|title=Redirekcija|work=revijad.co.me|accessdate=8 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522012809/http://www.revijad.co.me/index.php?nivo=3&rubrika=&datum=2009-01-14&brojms=342&clanak=756|archivedate=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nGolubovi\u0107 got arrested in Greece on 25 December 2002 on a Serbian arrest warrant because of the criminal citation stemming from the July 1994 incident with Milorad Majki\u0107. The citation claimed Golubovic slapped Majkic while trying to extort DM 10,000 from him. Following three and a half month stay in [[detention]], he got [[extradition|extradited]] to Serbia on 16 April 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/info/vesti/index.php?yyyy=2003&mm=04&dd=16&nav_category=16&nav_id=106263|title=Izru\u010den Kristijan Golubovi\u0107|work=B92|date=16 April 2003|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> At the first court date in May 2003, Golubovic denied extorting Majic but admitted to slapping him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.blic.rs/stara_arhiva/hronika/43964/Samo-sam-ga-osamario|title=Samo sam ga o\u0161amario|newspaper=[[Blic]]|date=27 May 2003|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was arrested in [[Operation Sablja]], a crackdown on organized crime in Serbia following [[Prime Minister]] [[Zoran \u0110in\u0111i\u0107]]'s assassination, for being the leader of a criminal group that extorted \u20ac 15,000 from a businessman from [[Sremska Mitrovica]]; the sentence was initially 6 years, but the case ended with 1 and a half year.<ref name=BLIC/>\n\nOn the night of 17 March 2004, Golubovi\u0107 and famous Serbian [[turbo-folk]] singer [[Ceca Ra\u017enatovi\u0107]] (widow of the murdered ''Arkan'') gathered protesters in front of the government building in Belgrade to rally against the [[2004 unrest in Kosovo|situation in Kosovo]] where more than 36 [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Serbian Orthodox churches]] had been burned the same day in an outbreak of [[Albanians|Muslim Albanian]] violence against the [[Serbs|Serb]] natives of the province.\n\nOn 12 December 2005, Golubovi\u0107 got sentenced to six years of prison by the Special Court in Belgrade on illegal arms and [[racketeering]] charges of trying to extort \u20ac 15,000 from Petar \u017deravi\u0107, a former policeman from Sremska Mitrovica from April to June 2005 and the extortion of \u20ac 3,000 and [[gold jewelry]] theft from the Arsi\u0107's, a married couple from [[Aran\u0111elovac]]. The case was appealed ant the sentence got reduced to four and a half years, which he served at Zabela prison in [[Po\u017earevac]].<ref name=\"vreme-jun-2010\"/>\n\nOn 9 January 2009, he was released from the [[Po\u017earevac]] prison where he had spent four and a half years.<ref name=N247>{{cite web |url=http://www.novosti247.com/kristijan-golubovic-se-posvetio-duhovnom-zivotu-sada-radi-u-crkvi |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222031255/http://www.novosti247.com/kristijan-golubovic-se-posvetio-duhovnom-zivotu-sada-radi-u-crkvi |archivedate=2012-02-22 }}</ref>\nHe made a rap song together with [[Elitni odredi]] called ''Jack i Chivas'' (''[[Jack Daniel's|Jack Daniels]] and [[Chivas Regal]]''). He was denied entry to [[Croatia]] in 2009 when he was going to fight in the ''Millenium Fighting Challenge'' MMA event held in [[Split (city)|Split]], mayor [[\u017deljko Kerum]] denied his entrance and police were ready to stop Golubovi\u0107 if he would enter Croatia is all because he called the Croatian authorities To say that there was explosives on the bus that was entering Croatia a tactic Golobovic used previously, smiling as  he told reporters that he had a bad nightmare of losing badly to Kerum and that  no one scared his nerves  as much, they were out of control and I had to throw up, so he had to think of an ingenious plan, it's just like pulling the fire alarm in school when not ready for a big test, ha ha he laughed at this like it was a big joke,   Kerum said joke is on him, if he wants to live like a coward let him live it not me, he knows the deal with me in or out the ring, it's maybe his last fight when he was beat up and historical defeat he let down everything he stands for is giving him a nightmare the Albanian took his heart out ! So he can't  \"He has a history of crime and suspicious relations with the criminal world and is not welcomed to Split or Croatia, nor be a sport example\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/72161/kerum-kristijan-golubovic-ne-moze-biti-dobrodosao-u-split |title=Kerum: Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 ne mo\u017ee biti dobrodo\u0161ao u Split |magazine=[[Nacional (weekly)]] |trans-title=Kerum: Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 cannot be welcome in Split |language=Croatian |date=24 November 2009 |accessdate=24 July 2012 |archivedate=2012-07-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69OXdIpzK?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/72161/kerum-kristijan-golubovic-ne-moze-biti-dobrodosao-u-split }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bljesak.info/content/view/42404/159/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129025211/http://www.bljesak.info/content/view/42404/159/ |archivedate=2009-11-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 January 2010, Golubovi\u0107, his mother and five other members of his criminal group were arrested in Belgrade on charges of [[narcotics]] trade in [[Novi Pazar]] and Belgrade starting in August 2009. He and his two companions were intercepted at a drug exchange of 25&nbsp;grams of marijuana when they exited [[St. Mark's Church, Belgrade|Saint Mark's Church]].<ref name=N247/><ref name=BLICH>{{cite web|url=http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Hronika/172763/Kristijan-preuzeo-heroin-u-crkvi|title=Blic Online - Kristijan preuzeo heroin u crkvi|work=Blic Online|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> He had the previous week been stopped by police who found 10&nbsp;grams of marijuana in his [[Audi TT]]. His friend in the car claimed the marijuana was his and Golubovi\u0107 was held for 4 hours before being set free, his friend is awaiting trial. The police then searched his home in [[Vi\u0161njica, Serbia|Vi\u0161njica]] and found a gun and ammunition without a serial number, a Beretta was found in his mother's house.<ref name=N247/> He is to be sentenced for narcotics trade, illegal arms and explosives possession. They are all currently (April) in the central prison of Belgrade. He allegedly tried [[hanging|suicide by hanging]] in his cell the days following the arrest. The motive of the [[suicide attempt]] was that he felt devastated that he had caused the arrest of his mother who had nothing to do with this. She is quoted as having said, \"I should have aborted you\". He shares cells with \"Elez gang\", leader Darko Elez and [[Zemun clan]] hitman Nikola Baji\u0107. His wife was briefly held in March for the finding of a land mine in her car.<ref name=BLIC/><ref>http://www.glas-javnosti.rs/clanak/hronika/glas-javnosti-26-03-2010/kristijan-se-plasi-trovanja</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glassrpske.com/vijest/8/srbija/34581/lat/Kristijan-Golubovic-pokusao-samoubistvo.html|title=Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 poku\u0161ao samoubistvo|work=Glas Srpske|accessdate=8 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104224158/http://www.glassrpske.com/vijest/8/srbija/34581/lat/Kristijan-Golubovic-pokusao-samoubistvo.html|archive-date=4 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>http://www.glas-javnosti.rs/clanak/hronika/glas-javnosti-02-04-2010/kristijan-golubovic-optuzen-za-trgovinu-drogom</ref>\n\n===2010s===\nDuring the 2010s, Kristijan was constantly in and out of prison, awaiting trial. In early January 2016, Kristijan released a rap song with ''DeNiro'' called ''\u017divim kao \u0160ef''. Also, on May 9, he had his third mixed martial arts fight, returning to the sport 6 years after his previous fight, which he won by disqualification. It was held in [[Vienna]] against '''Agim Abdullahu'''. He lost the fight by [[TKO]] in the first round. After the fight, Kristijan made statements  on social media that it was rigged and unfair, claiming it was the referee's fault.\nOn March 16, Golubovi\u0107 was sentenced to 4 years and 1 month in the Zabela prison. While in prison. On October 9, Golubovi\u0107 released another rap song called ''Moj Czas'' along with a fellow rapper from [[Poland]] called ''Brex''.\n\n==Popular culture==\nIn 1993 he appeared on the album ''[[Zbogom, Srbijo]]'' by [[Serbia]]n band [[Riblja \u010corba]], singing with band's [[Lead vocalist#Frontperson|frontman]] [[Bora \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107]] in the song ''Kamenko i Kremenko'' (Serbian names of ''Fred'' and ''Barney'' from ''[[The Flintstones]]'').\n\nHe was part of highly popular [[reality television|reality shows]], such as [[Farma (Serbian TV series)|''Farma'']] and ''[[Parovi]]''.\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws= \n| nc= \n| ko-wins= 1\n| ko-losses= \n| sub-wins= \n| sub-losses= 1\n| dec-wins= \n| dec-losses= \n| dq-wins= 1\n| dq-losses= \n| other-wins= \n| other-losses= \n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|align=center|2\u20131\n| Agim Abdullahu\n| Submission (guillotine choke)\n| Night of Gladiator\n| {{dts|2015|May|09}} \n|align=center| 1\n|align=center| N/A\n| [[Vienna]], Austria\n| \n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win \n|align=center|2\u20130\n|Stanislav Drakov \n| DQ (Drakov bit Golubovic's finger)\n| WKN Serbia - Kings of the Ring \n| {{dts|2009|December|13}} \n|align=center| 2 \n|align=center| N/A\n| [[Ni\u0161]], Serbia \n| \n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win \n|align=center|1\u20130\n|Marian Rusu \n| TKO (leg injury)\n| Ultra FC - Stop the Crime  \n| {{dts|2009|October|31}} \n|align=center| 1\n|align=center| 0:24\n| [[Subotica]], Serbia \n| \n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://kristijankikigolubovic.weebly.com/ Official website]\n*{{Sherdog}}\n* [http://blip.tv/play/hKYmgY%2BMYAI/ Documentary See You in the Obituary Full Movie]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-4824402008949268606 Interview with Kristijan Golubovi\u0107 on Palma television]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golubovic, Kristijan}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Escapees from Greek detention]]\n[[Category:Heavyweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mobsters from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Munich]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Serbian male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Serbian mobsters]]\n[[Category:Serbian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriates in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:delinquent\u2192Juvenile delinquency,detention\u2192detention (imprisonment),TKO\u2192Technical knockout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kristijan_Golubovi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Zenit (camera)", "text_new": "{{short description|Soviet camera company}}\n{{about|the Russian camera and photographic equipment brand|the astronomic or geodetic instruments directed to the zenith|Zenith camera|other uses|Zenit (disambiguation)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Original research|date=March 2010}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2007}}\n}}\n[[File:ZENIT 12SD (XP) camera, production date May 27 1991 in USSR on Krasnogorsk plant, serial number 91023463, lens serial number 91189821.jpg|alt=ZENIT 12SD (XP) camera, manufactured on May 27 1991 in USSR on Krasnogorsk plant, serial number 91023463, lens serial number 91189821|thumb|upright=1.5|ZENIT 12SD (XP)]]\n'''Zenit''' ({{lang-ru|\u0417\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0301\u0442}}) is a [[Russia]]n (and formerly [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]) [[camera]] brand manufactured by [[Krasnogorskiy Zavod|KMZ]] in the town of [[Krasnogorsk, Moscow Oblast|Krasnogorsk]] near [[Moscow]] since 1952 and by [[BELOMO|BelOMO]] in [[Belarus]] since the 1970s. The Zenit [[trademark]] is associated with [[35 mm format|35&nbsp;mm]] [[Single-lens reflex camera|SLR]] cameras. Among related brands are [[Zorki]] for 35&nbsp;mm [[rangefinder camera]]s, '''Moskva''' (Moscow) and '''Iskra''' for [[Medium format (film)|medium-format]] folding cameras and [[Horizon (camera)|Horizon]] for panoramic cameras. In the 1960s and 1970s, they were exported by [[Mashpriborintorg]] to 74 countries.<ref name=\"Mashpriborintorg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ussrphoto.com/Wiki/default.asp?WikiCatID=38&ParentID=4&ContentID=601&Item=MashPriborIntorg+1978|title=USSRPhoto.com - Russian / Soviet Cameras Wiki Catalog - MashPriborIntorg 1978|website=www.ussrphoto.com|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe name is sometimes spelled '''Zenith''' in English, such as the manuals published by the [[United Kingdom|UK]] Zenit-importer [[Technical & Optical Equipment (London) Ltd.|TOE]].<ref name=\"toemanual\">{{cite web|url=http://www.commiecameras.com/sov/35mmsinglelensreflexcameras/cameras/zenit/manuals.htm|title=Zenit SLR Camera Manuals|website=www.commiecameras.com|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref> However, TOE's imported camera bodies as from 1963 retained the \"Zenit\" badges. The early Zorki-based models before that time were labelled \"Zenith\" in a handwritten style of script.\n\n==Digital models==\n\nDuring the 2018 Photokina expo, Zenit announced that it was resuming camera and lens production for the M-mount, as well as for unspecified Nikon and Canon mounts in 2019.<ref>https://www.cinema5d.com/zenit-m-with-35mm-f-1-0-lens-russian-legendary-brand-enters-digital-age-interview-and-footage/</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id=U5NDAq0B9co|title=Zenit M with 35mm F/1.0 Lens \u2013 Russian Legendary Brand Enters Digital Age \u2013 Interview and Footage}}</ref>\n\n===Zenit M===\nThe digital Zenit M camera was released in a limited edition set with the Zenitar-M 35mm F/1.0 lens.  The camera was produced in partnership with Leica, and the digital components derived to some extent from the full-frame Leica M (typ 240) series.  The edition comprised 500 units: fifty units with a black finish and 450 in silver.  Russian firmware drives the camera, and the chassis was designed in Krasnogorsk.<ref>https://www.cinema5d.com/zenit-m-with-35mm-f-1-0-lens-russian-legendary-brand-enters-digital-age-interview-and-footage/</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id=U5NDAq0B9co|title=Zenit M with 35mm F/1.0 Lens \u2013 Russian Legendary Brand Enters Digital Age \u2013 Interview and Footage}}</ref>\n\n===Zenitar-M===\nTwo further M-mount Zenitar lenses are set for release circa March 2019: the Zenitar-M 21mm F/2.8 and the Zenitar-M 50mm F/1.0.<ref>{{YouTube|id=U5NDAq0B9co|title=Zenit M with 35mm F/1.0 Lens \u2013 Russian Legendary Brand Enters Digital Age \u2013 Interview and Footage}}</ref>\n\n===Zenit-Leica Collaboration===\nA second digital camera of an entirely new design is planned for release by 2020; also in collaboration with Leica.  This camera will make use of a different lens line.<ref>{{YouTube|id=U5NDAq0B9co|title=Zenit M with 35mm F/1.0 Lens \u2013 Russian Legendary Brand Enters Digital Age \u2013 Interview and Footage}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early years===\n[[File:Zenit (458841015).jpg|thumb|Zenit, first model, 1952]]\n[[File:Zenit-s.jpg|thumb|Zenit-S (Synchronized), 1955]]\nThe above '''Zenit''' was based on the [[Zorki]] rangefinder camera (a copy of the [[Leica Camera#Early models|Leica II]]). In transforming the Zorki into an SLR, the simplest approach was taken: the rangefinder housing was removed from the top and replaced by a plain ground-glass screen and prism; a mirror was added below, with a rope-and-pulley setting system  and the [[M39 lens mount|M39]]\u00d71 thread mount was pushed forward to make room for the mirror inside.\n\nDuring the first years of production (until the Zenit-E of 1967) Zenit camera development coincided with that of the Zorki cameras. The Zenit-S had PC-synchro for external flash units (almost like the Zorki-S) and the Zenit-3M also had an RF-sibling, the Zorki-6. For an SLR, the Pentaprism of all classical Zenits was undersize, with the viewfinder showing about two-thirds of the actual frame-size.\n\n===Zenit-E and its successors===\n[[File:Zenit-E Camera with Industar 50mm lens.jpg|thumb|Zenit E with Industar 50-2 50/3.5 Lens and Selenium-cell lightmeter]]\n[[File:Zenit e.jpg|thumb|Zenit E with Helios 44-2 lens, made in 1971]]\nDuring 1967 through 1969 KMZ built an automatic die-cast moulding line, allowing mass camera production. Camera production switched to the [[M42 lens mount|M42\u00d71]] thread (also known as [[Praktica]] thread) and an instant-return mirror was also developed. This led to one of the most famous Zenits \u2014 '''Zenit-E''' which saw (including its subtypes) over 12 million produced. A heavy and tough camera with a mechanism that was of exceedingly simple design along the lines of \"what isn't there, can't go wrong\".  Automatic diaphragm functionality was not available until the introduction of the Zenit-EM, which used a direct mechanism linking the shutter release button to the aperture mechanism, significantly increasing the effort required to release the shutter.  Production included both M39\u00d71 and M42\u00d71 mounts for the Zenit E and [[Zenit B]] models.  Later models were only produced in the M42\u00d71 with the Pentax K mount available for the latest models.\n\nTowards the end of the 20th century, the Zenit-E heritage became an obstacle to the development of more modern Zenit models. This was because almost all low-end Zenits until the recent 412DX have been based on the Zenit-E die-cast chassis, complying with the local philosophy that a crude but affordable camera was better than no camera.\n{{anchor|zenit_ttl}}<!-- Used for [[Zenit TTL]] redirect linking to subsection here -->\nThe major events of the further development of Zenit-E line was:\n*Introduction of an automatic 'jumping' [[Diaphragm (optics)|diaphragm]] on the '''Zenit-EM'''\n*[[Through-the-lens|TTL]] metering system (instead of a non-coupled Selenium-cell lightmeter) on the '''Zenit-TTL'''\n*Switching to the [[Pentax K mount]] \u2014 '''Zenit-122K'''\n*DX-code introduction (instead of manual ISO-speed switch) \u2014 '''Zenit-412DX'''\n\nThe Zenit-E was also sold with the [[Moscow 1980 Olympics]] emblem.\n\n===Advanced models===\n[[File:Zenit 122 camera.jpg|thumb|Zenit 122]]\nThe first attempt to make high-end professional camera by KMZ was the '''Start''' in 1958. This camera had a full set of shutter speeds (from 1 sec to 1/1000), a lens with an automatic diaphragm in a unique [[breech-lock]] mount, and even a knife for cutting-off part of the unexposed film. The photographer could choose between a pentaprism and waist-level finders. The grave disadvantage of the Start is blamed on lack of lenses; only one lens (the [[Helios (lens brand)|Helios]]-44 f2/58) was ever made for the proprietary Start mount directly.\n\nWith the success of the Zeiss-Ikon Contaflex of the mid-1950s and its follow-ups in form of the Bessamatic, Retina- and Paxette-reflex, Zenit's next attempt was the '''Zenit-4''' (1964), '''-5''' and '''-6''' cameras. These were based on a [[Voigtl\u00e4nder]] Bessamatic-type mount with Compur-type iris-shutter near the lens elements. The poor durability and high manufacturing cost of this concept in contrast to the classical barebone Zenit design based on ultimate simplicity showed KMZ to have taken a wrong track: Nevertheless, the Zenit-5 was the first Soviet motor-driven SLR camera, and the first Soviet zoom lens (Rubin-1c 2.8/37\u201380, based on [[Voigtl\u00e4nder]] Zoomar design) featured in the '''Zenit-6'''.\n\nFollowing this, there were two more attempts to make high-end photographic equipment, namely the '''Zenit-7''' (1968) and '''Zenit-D''' (1969). Both were based on the completely new cloth-curtain shutter construction. The '''Zenit-D''' had automatic exposure mode. Its shutter was sped up to achieve X-sync at 1/125. Each of these had its own bayonet mount (\"mount 7\" and \"mount D\" respectively) which helped to utilize the camera's most advanced features. There were plans to develop a full line of optics for these cameras but the new shutter was too complicated and unreliable. Production was cancelled shortly after, and the only lens made for new mounts were the standard types. The '''Start''', '''Zenit-7''' and '''Zenit-D''' utilized the same normal lens \u2014 a Helios-44 2/58. The Zenit-D is one of the rarest Zenit cameras \u2014 only 63 cameras were produced.\n\nThe Zenit 12-XP With its Helios f2/58mm lens and cloth shutter was widely sold by US Eastern camera stores. Many with the Zenit name covered with their \"USA\" brand. This Metallic re-badge was easy enough to gently pry off to see the true name Zenit. The TTL meter was fairly accurate and took decent shots. The 1981 price was $110 usa. The Russians believed that 58mm more closely matched the Human normal range than the standard 50mm used worldwide as a normal lens. It also had a T setting for timed exposures making it a good choice for yearly fireworks displays. The \"T\" setting locked the shutter open allowing a tripod mounted camera to be used with an index card to manually open for few bursts of fire works and then close and reset.\n\nAfter one more unsuccessful camera ('''Zenit-16''') which was produced in very small quantities, in 1979 production of the '''Zenit-19''' began. This was a camera with an original electromagnet-driven focal-plane shutter, M42 lens mount, and shutter speeds from 1 sec to 1/1000.  X-sync at 1/60 or 1/125 (camera was modified during production). The camera has only manual shooting mode (with a TTL-meter and a needle indicator of the proper exposition in the viewfinder). The Zenit-19 was, perhaps, the top-of-the-line Soviet [[M42 lens mount]] camera.\n\n===Pentax-K mount series===\nIn 1984 the '''Zenit-automat''' entered production. This had a [[Pentax K mount]] (which was proposed as an [[open standard]] by [[Pentax]] and distributed freely{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}) and a focal shutter with horizontal-travel cloth curtains. The only operation mode was [[aperture-priority]]. The camera was modified in 1988, to include shutter FZL-84 with vertical-travel metal curtains, and was reissued as the '''Zenit-AM'''. The '''Zenit-AM2''' was a cheaper version of the AM without the self-timer.\n\nNext in line was the '''Zenit-APK'''. Its distinguishing feature was the introduction of a manual shutter mode in addition to aperture-priority. The original FZL-84 shutter was also changed to a licensed 'Copal Square' shutter.\n\nThe most recent model is the '''Zenit-KM''' of 2001. This is the second microprocessor-controlled camera in the Zenit range (the first one was the second variant of the '''Zenit-automat''' camera), and the second (after the Zenit-5) motor-driven SLR camera built by KMZ. Shutter speeds range from 1/2000 to 1 sec (and up to 16 sec in Auto mode). X-sync is 1/125 sec, and the camera includes both manual shutter and aperture-priority modes as well as DX-coding from 50 to 3200 [[International Organization for Standardization|ISO]]. In 2004, the KM received some improvements and was renamed to the '''Zenit-KM Plus'''\n\nThe Zenit-KM Plus was the final Zenit camera to be produced; {{As of|2005|lc=on}} all SLR camera production at the Krasnogorsk factory ceased. These highly interesting ultimate Zeniths would have been major sellers on Western markets during the \"SLR-decade\" of the 1970s.{{According to whom|date=June 2013}} However, they appeared at a time when their market-segment was saturated with second-hand equipment, so no major importer looked at them{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}. One of the characteristics of Soviet camera manufacture was that the capability of its designers was well ahead of that of its policy-makers.  The 20-year overdue replacement of the external selenium cell of the Zenit E by TTL-metering is said to be the work of an employee who made a conversion on his own accord.    <!-- **** WHAT ABOUT THE BELARUS PLANT? **** **** It closed a cameras production in 1990! **** -->\n\n===Soviet Export Policy===\nIn the West, the success of the Zenit line can be focused on the United Kingdom, primarily due to the marketing activity and service of TOE, and secondly the originally heavy UK tax-load of up to two-thirds on imported precision cameras.\nSubstantial quantities were later sold by German discounters like Foto-Quelle and Neckermann. The main criticism of the USSR exporters at the time was that they could only supply hopelessly outdated equipment like the Zenit E that they had been directed to produce in quantity, despite having the capacity to produce more technically advanced products that might have been attractive to Western buyers. TOE were fighting a constant battle with their USSR-suppliers in this direction, having to fill the gap left by the excellent but not-for-export Soviet lenses which would have been a major selling-point, by a hodge-podge selection of second-rate mass-market optics from Japan, albeit under the \"Helios\" label.\n\n===Standard Zenit Lenses===\nThe original Zenit came with the sturdy click-stop four-element 3.5/50mm Zeiss Tessar copy under the \"Industar\" designation.  Early aluminium variants made in several different bodies were finely blue-coated, whereas the later mass-produced black version was either partially or un-coated with no visible colour on the glass. They were sharp but gave the typically \"foggy\" image of an uncoated lens with bright lighting.  With the iris ring sitting inside the focussing ring it was impossible to focus at full aperture followed by stopping down, as this moved the point of focus.  What makes these lenses interesting is their very compact \"pancake\" design. The concept of the makers was to offer a sharp Tessar-type lens of the simplest possible body construction, leaving out all progress made in this field since 1945.  The most prominent lens is the 6-element 2.0/58mm \"Helios\" based on the pre-war Zeiss Biotar (US Patent 1,786,916 (W.Mert\u00e9, 1930) Zenit also manufactures several [[Tair (lens)|Tair]] lenses in different focal lengths of which some were of 4-element pre-war Zeiss Sonnar design with the cemented second and ultra-fat third element.\n\n==Camera models==\n\n===Early cameras===\nBottom Loading\n* Zenit (1953\u201356)\n* Zenit-S (S stands for flash sync, 1955\u201361)\n* Zenit-3 (1960\u201362)\n\nHinged Back\n* Kristall/Crystal (1961\u201362)\n* Zenit-3M (modified Kristall, 1962\u201370)\n\n==={{anchor|Zenit 4|Zenit 5|Zenit 6}}Zenit 4 line semiautomatic cameras===\n* Zenit 4\n* Zenit 5\n* Zenit 6\n\n{{anchor|Zenit DKL-mount lenses}}List of Zenit DKL-mount (\"\u0411\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u0426\") lenses:\n\n*Mir-1\u0426 37mm f2.8\n*Vega-3 50mm f2.8\n*Helios-65\u0426 52mm f2.8\n*Jupiter-25\u0426 85mm f2.8\n*Tair-38\u0426 133mm f2.8\n*Rubin-1\u0426 37-80mm f2.8\n\n===Zenit-E line===\n\n====Models with a Selenium cell lightmeter====\n[[File:Zenith by RustedStrings.jpg|thumb|Zenit ET with Helios 44-2 lens]]\n[[File:Zenit-E 0544.jpg|thumb|Zenit-E]]\n[[File:Zenit 12XP.jpg|thumb|Zenit 12xp]]\n[[File:Zenit TTL (front top angle).jpg|thumb|Zenit TTL]]\n* Zenit-E\n* Zenit-EM, Produced between 1972-1984 by KMZ.\n* Zenit-ET\n* Zenit-10\n* Zenit-11\n\n====Models without a Selenium lightmeter====\n* Zenit-V, also known as Zenit-B (identical to the E but no lightmeter)\n* Zenit-VM, also known as Zenit-BM (identical to the EM but no lightmeter)\n\n====Cameras with TTL-metering and M42 thread mount====\n[[File:Zenit 412.jpg|thumb|Zenit 412, one of the last models]]\n* Zenit-TTL\n* Zenit-12\n* Zenit-12xp, Zenit-12sd\n* Zenit-122\n* Zenit-122V, also known as Zenit-122B\n* Zenit-312m\n* Zenit-412DX\n* Zenit-412LS\n\n====Cameras with TTL-metering and Pentax K mount====\n* Zenit-122K\n* Zenit-212K\n\n===Cameras with non-standard mounts===\n* Start\n* Zenit-7\n* Zenit-D\n\n===M42 semi-automatic cameras===\n* Zenit-16\n* Zenit-19\n* Zenit-18 automatic camera\n* Zenit-MT-1 Surprise (half frame Zenit-19 variant)\n\n===Zenit-Ax line (Pentax K mount cameras)===\n[[File:Zenit am by igors jefimovs.jpg|thumb|Zenit-AM-2 camera and accessories]]\n* Zenit-Automat, also known as Zenit-Auto\n* Zenit-AM\n* Zenit-AM2\n* Zenit-APM\n* Zenit-APK\n* Zenit-KM\n* Zenit-KM plus\n\n===Zenit-DF line (Minolta / Rokkor mount cameras made by Seagull)===\n<small>Source</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.subclub.org/minchin/index.htm|title=CHINA|website=www.subclub.org|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref>\n* Zenit DF-2, same as the Seagull DF-2\n* Zenit DF-2ETM, same as the Seagull DF-2ETM\n* Zenit DF-300, same as the Seagull DF-300\n* Zenit DF-300x, same as the Seagull DF-300x2\n\n===Photosniper===\nOne oddity of the Zenit camera range is the so-called FotoSnaiper (or Photosniper) kit, which consists of a case (either leather or metal) a gunstock and shoulderstock, filters, a 300&nbsp;mm f4.5 [[Tair (lens)|Tair-3 lens]], a normal lens and a Zenit adapted for the gunstock (recognizable by the s designation, Zenit-ES, 122s etc.). The camera is actually held in the same manner as a rifle; hence the name \"Photosniper\".\n\n[[File:Photosniper - assembled.jpg|thumb|Photosniper 12S]]\nProduction Models\n\n* FS-2    (FED RF based)\n* FS-3    (Zenit-E based)\n* FS-12   (Zenit-12, Zenit-TTL based)\n* FS-12-3 (Zenit-12xp based)\n* FS-122  (Zenit-122 based)\n* FS-412  (Zenit-412DX based)\n\nLow Production and Prototype only\n\n* FS-4\n* FS-4M\n* FS-5\n\n==Enlargers==\n\nZenit manufactured a large range of [[enlarger]]s as well. Some of the best known are the models [[UPA-5]] and [[UPA-6]]. UPA-5 is a portable model which folds into a small suitcase.\nUPA-6 is a more sophisticated enlarger for producing color photo prints.\n\n== Citations ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Zenit cameras}}\nIn English\n* [http://www.zenit-foto.ru/ Homepage of KMZ]\n* [http://www.zenitcamera.com/catalog/cameralist-eng.html Complete KMZ cameras list]\n* [http://zorkiphoto.co.uk/2012/11/01/zenit-e-russian-camera-review/ Review of Zenit E by Stephen Dowling]\n* [http://members.tripod.com/rick_oleson/index-9.html Review of first Zenit by Rick Oleson]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080516000501/http://www.btinternet.com/~stowupland/start/index.html Soviet Start SLR Professional camera 1958-64 by Stephen Rothery]\n* [http://www.ussrphoto.com/Wiki/default.asp?WikiCatID=69&ParentID=1 USSRPhoto.com wiki catalog listing of all Zenit models]\n* [http://www.subclub.org/minchin/index.htm Zenit cameras made in China by Seagull]\n* [http://lensbeam.com/camera-review/zenit-cameras Zenit Cameras. Genealogy]\n\nIn Spanish\n* [http://instantes.net/blog/2009/11/manual-de-instrucciones-de-la-zenit-122-en-espanol/ Zenit 122 manual in Spanish]\n\nIn Russian\n* [http://www.zenitcamera.com/ The KMZ R&D Center site] features a Russian-language [http: